 against this history, Kandaswamy illustrates how the Black female body came to represent a series of interconnected dangers—to white citizenship, heteropatriarchy, and capitalist ideals of productivity —and how a desire to curb these threats drove state policy. In challenging dominant feminist historiographies, Kandaswamy builds on Black feminist and queer of color critiques to situate the gendered afterlife of slavery as central to the historical development of the welfare state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican American familiesxLegal status, laws, etc.xHistory. 0aAfrican American womenxLegal status, laws, etc.xHistory. 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditions. 0aHeterosexismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPublic welfarezUnited StatesxHistoryvSources. 0aRacism in public welfarezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRacism in public welfarezUnited States. 0aWelfare recipientsxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aWelfare recipientsxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aWomanism. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021629zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021629423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021629/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles